{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b64650004c9338cd", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# End-to-End Speech Recognition: A Survey\narXiv: 2303.03329\nAuthors: Rohit Prabhavalkar, Takaaki Hori, Tara N. Sainath, Ralf Schlüter, Shinji Watanabe\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Provides a comprehensive taxonomy of end-to-end ASR models categorized by how they handle alignment between acoustic frames and output labels.\n  2. Presents architectural improvements to basic end-to-end models, including model combinations, contextual biasing, advanced encoder/decoder structures, and integrated endpointing.\n  3. Details training aspects of end-to-end models, covering alignment handling, external language model integration, minimum error training, pretraining, and regularization.\n  4. Reviews decoding algorithms for end-to-end models, distinguishing between frame-synchronous and label-synchronous beam search, as well as various model fusion and vectorization techniques.\n  5. Discusses external language model types and their integration methods into end-to-end ASR, ranging from shallow and deep fusion to internal language model estimation.\n  6. Analyzes the relationship between end-to-end and classical HMM-based ASR systems, comparing their modeling properties, training paradigms, and performance trends.\n  7. Demonstrates the real-world deployment of end-to-end models in on-device production systems, highlighting latency and accuracy trade-offs.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/显式对齐-CTC, ASR/显式对齐-RNNT", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "c5053ff0-a080-4462-b865-0f8befe551c0", "uuid": "40e2c5ce-296e-4883-b368-c39cfc3c652b", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T13:34:46.180Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# End-to-End Speech Recognition: A Survey\narXiv: 2303.03329\nAuthors: Rohit Prabhavalkar, Takaaki Hori, Tara N. Sainath, Ralf Schlüter, Shinji Watanabe\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Provides a comprehensive taxonomy of end-to-end ASR models categorized by how they handle alignment between acoustic frames and output labels.\n  2. Presents architectural improvements to basic end-to-end models, including model combinations, contextual biasing, advanced encoder/decoder structures, and integrated endpointing.\n  3. Details training aspects of end-to-end models, covering alignment handling, external language model integration, minimum error training, pretraining, and regularization.\n  4. Reviews decoding algorithms for end-to-end models, distinguishing between frame-synchronous and label-synchronous beam search, as well as various model fusion and vectorization techniques.\n  5. Discusses external language model types and their integration methods into end-to-end ASR, ranging from shallow and deep fusion to internal language model estimation.\n  6. Analyzes the relationship between end-to-end and classical HMM-based ASR systems, comparing their modeling properties, training paradigms, and performance trends.\n  7. Demonstrates the real-world deployment of end-to-end models in on-device production systems, highlighting latency and accuracy trade-offs.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/显式对齐-CTC, ASR/显式对齐-RNNT", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
